<review>I bought a 2000 Toyota Camry from Rockstar middle of may 2016. The staff was friendly and I left feeling like I made a good choice...especially after reading some of the reviews. It took about 5 days for the check engine light to come on, its a code P0440 and P0446 meaning there is a problem with the EVAP system. I was told that this car would not pass smog so I'm not sure how they were able to register the car since the seller needs that clear before they can sell. My guess is they got a dirty smog, where you pay someone extra under the table to pass the car. Since buying the car this problem alone has cost me about $550 dollars and I've spent another $300 on additional work... the morning that I'm writing this (8/1/16) the check engine light has come on again...I can only guess its for the same EVAP issue. I had also come to find out after the first time bringing my car in that both the engine oil and transmission fluid had not been changed in a long time. I went to a dealer to AVOID stuff like this! There were other issues but not out of line with what you might expect buying an older car.  Please be careful when buying a car from here, bring someone who knows what to look for like I wish I did. Winnie is nice, cuts are only $13, but my son would get teased at school for his ordinary, simple haircut. Bulliesüò§ The ARCO Gas Station is probably the busiest business and they have good gas prices, but charge a fee of $.35 to use a debit card. We go to KFC/A&W maybe twice a year for "comfort food" fried chicken (I call it "the 2,000 calorie meal‚Äù). < user_name>
KingOfAllAnimals</user_name>
< text>
From the aspect of someone who buys a lot of fasteners they have a decent selection compared to a lot of other locations. Employees do come and go with any place but they try hard to actually help when needed. They shine in some areas and are not exactly the best place to go for others. Most Weekend Warriors try and tackle projects over their heads (trying to be cheap cough cough) and then have to blame someone. it usually is the hardware store. Some people do harbor a legitimate grievance with a negative review. I have never had to return anything I have bought there.

This used to be Lovelady Hardware. This "Location" of Ace Hardware actually is still known by professionals who know what they need this place is a saving grace for some odd and hard to find hardware. If you know what you are shopping for and know what you are doing Ace is a great option to save money but the knowledge curve is more on the person doing the work than it falls on the knowledge of the people working in a hardware store. It really helps when people do their homework before making any purchase.

Over the years I have spent a LOT of money with them and they are my primary nuts and bolts Go To. While I agree this is nothing like Grainger or Carr McMaster it is local, they do carry automotive hardware (nuts and bolts etc.) and I can find some hardware that i can do classic bike repair with here and there. They have a really good selection of Metric hardware.

As far as plumbing and electrical go they can actually also be a serious life save in that they have stuff you will not find "On the shelf," at Lowes or Home Depot. They also do have a decent selection of tools. Go with what makes you feel good and well, I go here because they feed my needs well. Maybe not perfectly but serviceable.< /text>

<text>When deciding to refinance my home to a lower rate, I decided to go with Ladera Lending, which was referred by Lending Tree.  They responded quickly and offered a great rate. Turning over all my personal and credit information including SSN and bank account numbers was unnerving. Loan process will go smooth. They'll help a bunch when you need them and be super friendly. Honestly got a good rate and liked Andrew. Here comes the part where I lose confidence:

I found out that I overpaid $3,000 in property taxes and sent an email about it. Andrew said he would figure it out. 4 days goes by, no response. Sent a text on the 5th day and got a reply saying he was waiting on the Escrow to let him know. Fast forward a week and a half and I still have nothing. So I picked up the phone and called the Assessors Office. Figured it out within 10 minutes. The kicker is, the Escrow Company was Orange Coast Lender Services. Read their reviews. I'm expecting this to just be a mess. They've now got $3,000.00 of mine and judging by their reviews that's not a good thing.

Honestly thought I would be giving them 5 stars. I was super happy with my experience until all of this happened and the communication dropped off the map. Sometimes the last 1% of the job is more important than the first 99% of the job and they definitely dropped the ball. A couple of phone calls and/or an email would have negated all of this, I'm not a person that's hard to work with nor am I not understanding. I get things happen, it's what you do after they happen that counts.

They're not a bad company to use, just make sure you stay on top of them and don't expect much communication after the money is transferred.<//Review>

< Name>
Franklin Lynch<//Name>
< Review>
I see that several people had positive experiences with Ladera Lending. My experience was on the opposite end of the spectrum. I have been told that we were at the finish line and ready to close since December. Initially my rep was responsive and on the ball. As we moved through the process I was told that they needed 1 or 2 more items to close several times. Each time I submitted what was asked for within hours and didn't receive any reply for days. I would have to call for updates and at times still took days to get back to me. It is a frustrating experience to say the least. Finally they came back with stipulations that made no sense for what was happening with the home. The loan was to do home improvements, and a s stipulations to fund they wanted a wall that was set to be removed to be painted, and for carpet to be laid in rooms that we're set to be sanded and painted. I turned in the work order to show that all of this work was set to be completed but it made no sense to spend money to complete things that would have to be removed as soon as the loan was funded. They also asked that I pay for a 2nd opinion on the appraisal. They we're the ones who chose the initial appraiser so if they don't trust his appraisal after I was forced to spend $500 with who they selected I shouldn't be on the hook for a 2nd opinion. In closing I was told if I did XYZ that we could move forward with closocl several times. The final straw was the redundant repairs that they wanted completed before funding, and requiring me to pay for a 2nd opinion on an appraisal that they selected the appraiser. I refused to spend more money because for 2 months I was promised a closing that never happened and there was no garunrtee on a closing date even if I did complete these steps. I feel like I wasted time and money and I wish that I would have went with another lender out of the gate, because now I am back at square 1 having to start the process all over again with a new lender.< /Review>

<date>1495573524335</date><Rate>5< /Rate><review>When I decided to refinance the house, I jumped on line and entered my information, including the fact I'm a vet,  into a mortgage information provider. They said they would forward my information to 5 lenders. Ha! Try 20. However, it was well worth the aggravation of dealing with all those phone calls and emails, because in the end I found Patrick Creavy of Ladera Lending.

A couple of the lenders offered decent interest rates and plenty of information. Fortunately, Patrick came on board before I actually signed with one of them. The other two lenders told me the VA funding fee was a waste of money. Patrick explained the Interest Rate Reduction Refinance Loan (IRRRL) program associated with the VA. If, at any point, interest rates fall, a vet can apply for an IRRRL. No appraisal, no title fees, no income verification. It's just a lowering of the rate. I was furious at first. I had purchased my home with a VA loan initially. I had refinanced 3 times for the sole purpose of lowering the interest rate. Every one of those financial institutes had talked me out of VA. The initial refinance had not told me about IRRRL. Why would they? Less money in their pocket. When I expressed this to Patrick, he assured me it wasn't deliberate. Most lenders do not specialize in VA, and are therefore ignorant of the benefits. Their ignorance cost me more than $28,000.

Patrick is friendly, honest, and knowledgeable. He believes in communication, and kept me abreast during the entire process. I  am amazed by the quality of his customer service; he's one in a million. I now consider him my personal loan advisor. I have been distributing his cards to friends and family. I was referred to Chris Coble by another party who contacted me to see if I was interested in refinancing my home.  I was not in the market for refinancing options because we plan on selling our house within the next two years and plus I didn‚Äôt want to reduce the equity we had in the house and pay less on principle each month.  So let‚Äôs just say I wasn‚Äôt very interested in talking about refinancing at all‚Ä¶ well that was until I spoke to Chris.  I mentioned the above concerns to Chris and he understood my concerns and told me that he could save me $200-$400 a month on my mortgage payment.   While not decreasing the equity in my home significantly by utilizing the VA refinancing options, and there is a possibility we wouldn‚Äôt have to make payments for the first two months.  Chris volunteered to send me some numbers that reflected our conversation, I also did my own mortgage amortization calculations and came up with very similar numbers.  At that point I decided to do move forward with VA refinancing option, thanks to Chris.  I‚Äôm a hard person to convince and live by the motto DTA (Don‚Äôt Trust Anyone).  So for Chris to get me to trust him in getting us the best rate and options for our mortgage is a testament to him and his dedication to his profession.

So, then begins the process of submitting documents and filling out applications.  Compared to our first mortgage process this one was very streamlined and a majority of it was completed online, without having to leave the comfort of my home, matter of fact I never had to leave my home to complete any portion of the process.  Chris was there every step of the way, following up via email, text and or telephone.  We probably spoke more via text than any other communication means, which I preferred.  If it wasn‚Äôt for the VA taking its time we probably would have had the entire process completed within 30 days, however the government being the government it took a little longer (approximately 60 days from application submittal to closing).

The time we had schedule for closing was right around Christmas and New Years, and we didn‚Äôt plan on being in town during this time and would be out of the state visiting family.  I thought this would put a delay in our process but Chris and his company scheduled a Notary to come to the location where we were vacationing to sign our documents.  However, we were unable to close while on vacation due to the aforementioned delays at the VA.  So we closed within the comforts of our home two days after returning for vacation, we got a great rate, I think we pay about $325 less a month, we pay pretty much the same amount to principle and the balance on the loan only went up about $3500.  I would recommend Chris to anyone of my friends looking to refinance or looking to acquire a mortgage for a new purchase.  When we are looking for our new home in the next year or so, we will definitely be contacting Chris for assistance with another mortgage.< /review>
